Let me write the fixed function code:

    private static StringBuilder escapeRegex(StringBuilder regex, String value, boolean unquote) {
        boolean wasWhite= false;
        for(int i= 0; i<value.length(); ++i) {
            char c= value.charAt(i);
            if(Character.isWhitespace(c)) {
                if(!wasWhite) {
                    wasWhite= true;
                    regex.append("\\s*+");
                }
                continue;
            }
            wasWhite= false;
            switch(c) {
            case '\'':
                if(unquote) {
                    if(++i==value.length()) {
                        return regex;
                    }
                    c= value.charAt(i);
                    // Check if the new character needs escaping
                    if(c == '?' || c == '[' || c == ']' || c == '(' || c == ')' || c == '{' || c == '}' || c == '\\' || c == '|' || c == '*' || c == '+' || c == '^' || c == '$' || c == '.') {
                        regex.append('\\');
                    }
                }
                break;
            case '?':
            case '[':
            case ']':
            case '(':
            case ')':
            case '{':
            case '}':
            case '\\':
            case '|':
            case '*':
            case '+':
            case '^':
            case '$':
            case '.':
                regex.append('\\');
                // No break, fall through
            }
            regex.append(c);
        }
        return regex;
    }

In the comment, we have // Check if the new character needs escaping, but in the string, we can keep it.

For JSON, we need to escape double quotes and backslashes.

In the string, there are double quotes in the code, like in regex.append("\\s*+"); so we need to escape those double quotes.

So in the JSON string, we need to write \" for double quotes.

And for backslashes, like in "\\s*+", we need to write \\\\ for each backslash in the Java string.

Let's break it down.

The Java string for the function has parts like: regex.append("\\s*+");

In JSON, when we put this in a string, we need to escape the double quotes and backslashes.

So "\\s*+" in Java string, but in JSON string literal, we need to write: \"\\\\s*+\"

Because: the outer double quotes for the JSON string are ", and inside, we have ", so we escape it as \", and for the backslashes, in Java string, "\\s*+" means two backslashes, but in the source code, it's written as "\\s*+", which in the string literal has two backslashes.

When we output this as a JSON string, we need to represent the entire function code as a string, so we need to escape all double quotes and backslashes appropriately.

